Text: New team, new project! The 'Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning (PRML) lab and Ming Zhang from the anatomy department are working in collaboration to semi-automate the segmentation process of the plastination images.
Our project aim involves developing a user interface that is coupled with an underlying algorithm to assist in the segmentation of plastination images.
Last week, the team and I were working making our project poster and undergoing some underlying research.
In terms of team dynamic and project progression, everything is running smoothly.
We had our first 'unofficial' meeting with Jeremiah before our project pitches in his office.
We wanted to essentially get a better gauge on his interpretation of the project brief.
Although we left the office as a team feeling more sure about the specifications of the project, personally, I did not feel that I had completely understood the entire picture.
After the development of our project posters and having our second meeting with Jeremiah, I sought to ask my team members (multiple times lol) what each of their interpretation of the project was.
Overall, this helped establish my interpretation of the project and establishing that my team members and I were all on the same page.
I thought it was important to ask my team members, because, as a lesson from my last team project - making sure we are all on the same pageÂ  is extremely important for project progression.
Thus far, the team embodies cohesiveness and active willingness to participate.
During the meetings, everyone is always actively listening and sharing ideas.
I suppose this is due to the fact that we all have equal interest in this project - which is great!
The poster development was a breeze.
We all had our inputs in terms of design.
As of now, what we are doing well in is being a unit of a team.
After Teacher3's lecture about team management, Koko and I asked each other if there was some team rules we wanted to put in place.
'Transparency' was something I wanted the team to convey.

What that meant was essentially being honest about your thoughts of the progress, why you may not feel that would be a good idea, sharing ideas and having the willingness to convey that you may not understand something so that the rest of the team can help.
I suppose, it just goes under the umbrella of 'communication'.
Koko suggested 'having fun' as a rule lol (eg.Getting bubble tea on Monday).
We still need to communicate as a group to see if Toto and Rara have any rules that would like to apply : ).
Today, we will have a meeting to solidify our roles and specifications of the project with each other.
For the rest of the week, we will work on the first objective of our project - exploration of algorithm tools and UI tools.

I will also be emailing Jeremiah to set up a meeting with the Anatomy Dept.so that we can understand their needs for the project and further solidify more specifications in terms of the project (eg.what part of the image is most important to segment and establishing boundaries).
Fun week ahead!
